## Discovery Question Bank

> Deployment: asked live at technical discovery session
> or sent as questionnaire. Deep-dive why treatment
> complete for Environment & Access and
> Data Sources & Ingest.

### Environment & Access

**Q1. How many Entra tenants and Azure subscriptions
are in scope? Which subscription/resource group
hosts the Sentinel workspace?**
- Tenant = identity universe → Subscriptions =
  billing containers → Resource groups = folders
  → Log Analytics workspace = log database
  Sentinel bolts onto
- Why: Lighthouse scoped to subscription/RG.
  Wrong scope = access problems in week two.
  Second tenant may mean logs that cannot flow
  in via canned connectors. Hosting subscription
  owns the ingest bill.
- Use case: "Two tenants — corporate and subsidiary"
  → "Does subsidiary data flow into this workspace
  today and how?" Instant visibility gap found.

**Q2. Who are the named owners: workspace owner,
tenant admin, and who executes the Lighthouse
delegation?**
- Delegation requires Owner rights in their tenant.
  We cannot do it for them. Three-party structure
  means turnaround = proxy delay + end client delay.
- Use case: Recap email assigns delegation to a
  named person with a date. Tasks assigned to
  companies never get done.

**Q3. What is your Microsoft support plan level?**
- Basic = forums and prayer. Platform-side breakage
  only fixable via Microsoft ticket. We need
  Standard or above to file on their behalf.
- Use case: Firewall logs stop ingesting
  (Microsoft-side). Standard+ = sev-B same day.
  Basic = weeks of blindness on our SOC reputation.

**Q4. Any compliance or data residency constraints?**
- Workspace region is fixed. Retention may be
  legally mandated. Existing workspace = inherited
  decisions. Know which were compliance-driven
  before optimizing anything.
- Use case: Suggest retention cut, hear "PCI
  requires one year" = looks like we skipped
  discovery.

**Q5. Is the workspace onboarded to the Defender
portal or Azure portal only?**
- Our toolchain is Azure/Lighthouse-based.
  Post-July-2025 workspaces may be auto-onboarded.
  Defender XDR correlation can merge alerts
  differently — relevant to incident-triggered
  automation.
- Use case: "Our admin uses Defender portal" →
  "We manage via Azure/Lighthouse today with a
  Defender transition on our roadmap ahead of
  the 2027 retirement." Gotcha converted to
  roadmap evidence.

### Data Sources & Ingest

**Q1. Which connectors are enabled — actively
ingesting vs. connected-but-silent?**
- Enabled ≠ ingesting. Green checkmark does not
  mean data is flowing. Your audit workbook catches
  this — enabled connectors vs active tables =
  delta is your first finding.
- Use case: DeviceEvents empty 11 days, connector
  shows green. Licensing change broke it silently.
  You find it week one. Hero moment.

**Q2. What is the daily ingest volume, monthly
spend, and is a commitment tier in place?**
- PAYG vs commitment tier. Consistently above
  100GB/day on PAYG = burning money. Over-committed
  tier = paying for nothing.
- Use case: 150GB/day on PAYG → commitment tier
  math done → dollar savings in Phase 1 findings.
  Finance loves it.

**Q3. Which connectors are canned vs. custom?
For custom: who built it, who maintains it,
is there documentation?**
- Your 8-hour rule: re-engineering over 8 hours
  = cost conversation. Inherited custom connectors
  = inherited repair liability.
- Use case: Custom Logic App, no docs, auth token
  14 months old. Phase 1 risk item — not your
  fault it exists, your job to flag it before
  it breaks on your watch.

**Q4. What agents or forwarders are in play?
Who owns those boxes?**
- MMA retired August 2024 — unsupported, will
  break unpredictably. AMA needs properly scoped
  DCRs. Syslog forwarder VM = single point of
  failure for every device behind it.
- Use case: Forwarder VM gets OS patch, syslog
  service does not restart, firewall logs go
  silent. Your silent log detection fires but
  nobody knows who fixes the box. This question
  gives you that name before it happens.

**Q5. What sources do they consider critical —
the goes silent at 2am wake someone up list?**
- Foundation of silent log detection system and
  unified critical watchlist. Cannot build
  silent log detections without agreed sources
  and expected frequency baseline.
- Use case: "Firewall, Defender for Endpoint,
  Entra sign-in logs." Three rules, three watchlist
  entries, one controlled test demo in week three.

**Q6. Any planned source additions or retirements
in the next 90 days?**
- Retirements trigger false positive silent log
  alerts. Additions need detection rules ready
  the day the connector lights up.
- Use case: "Rolling out Defender for Identity
  in six weeks" → pull those detections into
  Phase 2 scope now.

**Q7. What is the retention setup — analytics
vs. basic/auxiliary tiers, any archive?**
- Detections only query analytics tier. High value
  logs in basic tier = detection blind spot.
  Everything in analytics at max retention =
  cost optimization opportunity.
- Use case: CommonSecurityLog at 365-day analytics
  retention, no compliance mandate → move beyond
  90 days to basic tier → dollar figure in
  Phase 1 findings.

